    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>The convention is to prefix the getter-method with \"is\" not the variale itself.</p>\n\n<p>e.g.</p>\n\n<pre><code>private boolean enabled;\n\npublic boolean isEnabled() {\n    return enabled;\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>and</p>\n\n<pre><code>private boolean storesOpen;\n\npublic boolean isStoresOpen() {\n    return storesOpen;\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<hr>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>isStoresOpen() doesn't make sense in English.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>It might not make sense grammatically, but it follows the convention and looks readable enough.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1355206,
      "reputation" : 33540,
      "user_id" : 1293744,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 44,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/AfomW.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Kumar Vivek Mitra",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1293744/kumar-vivek-mitra"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 4,
    "last_activity_date" : 1350582411,
    "creation_date" : 1350582411,
    "answer_id" : 12960607,
    "question_id" : 12960554,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p><strong>-</strong> <code>isEnabled()</code> can also be written as <code>getEnabled()</code> in <code>Java naming conventions</code>.</p>\n\n<p><strong>-</strong> Its just a good habit to follow the naming conventions, help when you are working with <code>Java Beans</code>.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 537054,
      "reputation" : 33059,
      "user_id" : 905762,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 77,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/JTgsI.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "John B",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/905762/john-b"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1350582447,
    "creation_date" : 1350582447,
    "answer_id" : 12960615,
    "question_id" : 12960554,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>In general I think code should be as easily readable as possible so that a method can almost be read as a paragraph (as espoused by <code>Clean Code</code>). Therefore, I would name the method to sound / read as easily as possible and go with the grammer rule of <code>are</code>. With modern IDEs it is easy to find methods without looking specifically for <code>get</code> / <code>is</code>.</p>\n\n<p>However, Kumar makes a good point about beans. A lot of tools will only look for <code>get</code> / <code>is</code>. In that case I might consider having both methods. One for ease of reading and one for tool use.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 76998,
        "reputation" : 29165,
        "user_id" : 220060,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 93,
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/56533d50fdfceb887852bf50be54678b?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
        "display_name" : "nalply",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/220060/nalply"
      },
      "edited" : false,
