    "body" : "<p>I can't remember which book this was from, but the essence is that code will be read many more times than it's written.  Write for readability.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1540981,
      "reputation" : 11632,
      "user_id" : 1435657,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 91,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/741aa8db6d8a87d8d9779889de1b8e70?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "asteri",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1435657/asteri"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1350582533,
    "creation_date" : 1350582533,
    "answer_id" : 12960639,
    "question_id" : 12960554,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>In object-oriented programming, this should rarely, if ever, occur since <code>Store</code> or <code>Cat</code> or what have you should be a separate class, with its own <code>isOpen()</code> or <code>isFuzzy()</code> method.  If you have a higher type, consider splitting down to the more atomic level that you're actually using.  In general, objects should not be plural at the lowest level.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 12404,
      "reputation" : 63291,
      "user_id" : 24396,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 74,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/160d6580f280b5e9e5a1188b32c4ef2d?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Steve Kuo",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/24396/steve-kuo"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 19,
    "last_activity_date" : 1350583633,
    "creation_date" : 1350583633,
    "answer_id" : 12960945,
    "question_id" : 12960554,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>The Java Bean specification says to use <code>get</code> for getters unless it's a <code>boolean</code> then use <code>is</code>. <code>are</code> is non-standard and will not be recognized by anything that expects standard Bean naming.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 305249,
      "reputation" : 44111,
      "user_id" : 615306,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 51,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5a11940d70233031c01ead6c0b62c990?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Kirill Rakhman",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/615306/kirill-rakhman"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1449688008,
    "last_edit_date" : 1449688008,
    "creation_date" : 1350587549,
    "answer_id" : 12962020,
    "question_id" : 12960554,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>In your question you're explicitly asking about getters. A getter returns some information about one instance of your class. For example you have a class <code>Store</code>. Now, <code>isStoreOpen</code> is a perfectly fine method name for a getter.</p>\n\n<p>Next, you mention a method that checks if all stores are open. This method isn't a getter at all, because it doesn't return information about one instance but for all. Of course unless there is a class <code>Stores</code>. If this is the case, you should rethink your design, because Java already has ways to store a number of instances, e.g. arrays or collections, so you don't have to write extra classes.</p>\n\n<p>If this is not the case, then this method name is perfectly fine. An alternative may be just <code>allStoresOpen</code> without the 'is'.</p>\n\n<p>TL;DR: If you're dealing with multiple instances, it's not a getter. If it is, your design is bad.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1146772,
      "reputation" : 32500,
      "user_id" : 1129332,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 61,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/KcrPN.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Ilya Gazman",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1129332/ilya-gazman"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 6,
    "last_activity_date" : 1617633115,
    "last_edit_date" : 1617633115,
    "creation_date" : 1351152587,
    "answer_id" : 13064288,
    "question_id" : 12960554,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<h1>What do you code, <strong>English</strong> or <strong>Java</strong>?</h1>\n<p>When I read Java code, I expect things to be structural. Boolean methods starting with <code>is</code> is a good structure.</p>\n<pre><code>return 0; \n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
