        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/6438573/cyphx"
      },
      "reply_to_user" : {
        "account_id" : 227523,
        "reputation" : 1423,
        "user_id" : 1775716,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 38,
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6e605d647f57a78df6b034c7ea88b74c?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
        "display_name" : "Michael P.",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1775716/michael-p"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1623079821,
      "post_id" : 22397978,
      "comment_id" : 119970583,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "@MichaelP. If this is something you are requiring in your codebase, then I would say you need to relook at the design of your classes. Your methods may well be expected to tell that there are no stores open, all stores open, is any store open, but if your require is strange enough that it warrants a relook at the design. You  can write a method <code>getCountOfOpenStores()</code> and use the number in the logic directly. As a class exposing methods to others, this would be my choice rather than  a method that checks if 2 stores are open. PS: This is all only from a practical implementation viewpoint."
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 75005,
      "reputation" : 15282,
      "user_id" : 215266,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 78,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3a8390f51211bcbf7f8df930327ee785?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "satur9nine",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/215266/satur9nine"
    },
    "is_accepted" : true,
    "score" : 164,
    "last_activity_date" : 1759803855,
    "last_edit_date" : 1759803855,
    "creation_date" : 1394779638,
    "answer_id" : 22397978,
    "question_id" : 12960554,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Consider using decent enough English and following Java naming conventions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>areStoresOpen()</code> could be <code>isEveryStoreOpen()</code></li>\n<li><code>areCatsCute()</code> could be <code>isEachCatCute()</code></li>\n</ul>\n<p>When in doubt of the right word I always like to hit up the thesaurus.</p>\n<p>These days AI could also be used to suggest something clever.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1339045,
      "reputation" : 4398,
      "user_id" : 1281120,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 64,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/13de5ad72b8b2b9afc3ccd9adca7d57d?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Arturas M",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1281120/arturas-m"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1460381929,
    "creation_date" : 1460381929,
    "answer_id" : 36550398,
    "question_id" : 12960554,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Quite honestly I would say definitely forget about the <code>are*</code> and stick with <code>is*</code>. Think of the <code>\"is\"</code> as the variable meaning and make a better name if possible. </p>\n\n<p>I would say is isStoresOpen doesn't sound that bad, but you can make isStoresAreOpen if that sounds better for you. </p>\n\n<p>But my general idea would be to stick to the conventions. Which is using \"get\" for getters and \"is\" for boolean types. Personally I think using \"is\" is sometimes already problematic. Yes - it does look good in \"if\" conditions, but sometimes I just write \"get\" when coding and check the drop down list for my needed variable and start wondering what's wrong and why I can't find it, then I realize it starts with \"is\"...</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 11081482,
      "reputation" : 21,
      "user_id" : 8136554,
      "user_type" : "unregistered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0db424345a5b0f2691895bf9a1015bfb?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Anil Kumar",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/8136554/anil-kumar"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1497005407,
    "last_edit_date" : 1497005407,
    "creation_date" : 1497004603,
    "answer_id" : 44455611,
    "question_id" : 12960554,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p><strong>isStoresOpen()</strong> in this StoresOpen is seems like a plural,</p>\n\n<p>When you follow that Java Naming Convention and Java Beans Standards, they have predefined prefix's for boolean and other type, so you should follow Java Beans Naming Convention. </p>\n\n<p>Let's come to your point\nWhen you see <strong>storesOpen</strong> as in an English prospective, yes it looks like plural.\nOnce again take deep observation into that word, </p>\n\n<p>Here</p>\n\n<p><strong>storesOpen</strong> is plural according to English grammar,</p>\n\n<p>The out come of the <strong>isStoresOpen</strong> is not plural, instead of it is singular or you can say it is scalar in terms of programming convention.</p>\n\n<p>It's out come is boolean, just true or false</p>\n\n<p>Not like your English plural statement <strong>true's</strong> or <strong>false's</strong></p>\n\n<p>Not an array of <strong>true</strong> or <strong>false</strong>, or not a collections of <strong>true</strong> or <strong>false</strong> </p>\n\n<p>So, here we can say that, here we are concerned with value that is return from that boolean bean method, not the name given to the property of class to point real world entity.</p>\n\n<p>One more important thing is, whenever such boolean properties are used in classes and those are used by predefined libraries in any framework, then framework with use prefix '<strong>is</strong>' for retrieving  boolean values, </p>\n\n<p>why means it's not that much of smarter than you as you know English grammar like plural/singular, multiplexer etc...</p>\n"
  } ],
  "owner" : {
    "account_id" : 48539,
    "reputation" : 3209,
    "user_id" : 144268,
    "user_type" : "registered",
    "accept_rate" : 82,
    "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/954f1de7431961fea8f4163d98cbd89b?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
